events.description: Sima Chi becomes emperor of the Jin dynasty in succession to his father, Sima Zhong, despite a challenge from his uncle, Sima Ying.
events.html: • 307 – Sima Chi becomes emperor of the Jin dynasty in succession to his father, Sima Zhong, despite a challenge from his uncle, Sima Ying.[1]

events.description: Æthelred I and Alfred the Great lead a West Saxon army to repel an invasion by Danelaw Vikings.
events.html: • 871 – Æthelred I and Alfred the Great lead a West Saxon army to repel an invasion by Danelaw Vikings.[2]

events.description: François Grimaldi, disguised as a monk, leads his men to capture the fortress protecting the Rock of Monaco, establishing his family as the rulers of Monaco.
events.html: • 1297 – François Grimaldi, disguised as a monk, leads his men to capture the fortress protecting the Rock of Monaco, establishing his family as the rulers of Monaco.[3]

events.description: The papal bull Romanus Pontifex awards the Kingdom of Portugal exclusive trade and colonization rights to all of Africa south of Cape Bojador.
events.html: • 1454 – The papal bull Romanus Pontifex awards the Kingdom of Portugal exclusive trade and colonization rights to all of Africa south of Cape Bojador.[4]

events.description: Louis XII of France marries Anne of Brittany in accordance with a law set by his predecessor, Charles VIII.
events.html: • 1499 – Louis XII of France marries Anne of Brittany in accordance with a law set by his predecessor, Charles VIII.[5]

events.description: The first Lithuanian-language book, the Catechism of Martynas Mažvydas, is published in Königsberg.
events.html: • 1547 – The first Lithuanian-language book, the Catechism of Martynas Mažvydas, is published in Königsberg.[6]

events.description: The premiere of George Frideric Handel's Ariodante takes place at the Royal Opera House, Covent Garden.
events.html: • 1735 – The premiere of George Frideric Handel's Ariodante takes place at the Royal Opera House, Covent Garden.[7]

events.description: Second Jacobite rising: Bonnie Prince Charlie occupies Stirling.
events.html: • 1746 – Second Jacobite rising: Bonnie Prince Charlie occupies Stirling.[8]

events.description: George Washington delivers the first State of the Union address in New York City.
events.html: • 1790 – George Washington delivers the first State of the Union address in New York City.[9]

events.description: The Dutch Cape Colony in southern Africa becomes the British Cape Colony as a result of the Battle of Blaauwberg.
events.html: • 1806 – The Dutch Cape Colony in southern Africa becomes the British Cape Colony as a result of the Battle of Blaauwberg.[10]

events.description: Charles Deslondes leads an unsuccessful slave revolt in the North American settlements of St. Charles and St. James, Louisiana.
events.html: • 1811 – Charles Deslondes leads an unsuccessful slave revolt in the North American settlements of St. Charles and St. James, Louisiana.[11]

events.description: War of 1812: Battle of New Orleans: Andrew Jackson leads American forces in victory over the British.
events.html: • 1815 – War of 1812: Battle of New Orleans: Andrew Jackson leads American forces in victory over the British.[12]

events.description: The Democratic Party of the United States is organized.
events.html: • 1828 – The Democratic Party of the United States is organized.[13]

events.description: US President Andrew Jackson announces a celebratory dinner after having reduced the United States national debt to zero for the only time.
events.html: • 1835 – US President Andrew Jackson announces a celebratory dinner after having reduced the United States national debt to zero for the only time.[14]

entities.name: National debt of the United States

events.description: American Civil War: Second Battle of Springfield.
events.html: • 1863 – American Civil War: Second Battle of Springfield.[15]

events.description: The United States Congress passes the bill to allow African American men the right to vote in Washington, D.C.
events.html: • 1867 – The United States Congress passes the bill to allow African American men the right to vote in Washington, D.C.[16]

events.description: Crazy Horse and his warriors fight their last battle against the United States Cavalry at Wolf Mountain, Montana Territory.
events.html: • 1877 – Crazy Horse and his warriors fight their last battle against the United States Cavalry at Wolf Mountain, Montana Territory.[17]

events.description: Herman Hollerith is issued US patent #395,791 for the 'Art of Applying Statistics' — his punched card calculator.
events.html: • 1889 – Herman Hollerith is issued US patent #395,791 for the 'Art of Applying Statistics' — his punched card calculator.[18]

events.description: President William McKinley  places Alaska under military rule.
events.html: • 1900 – President William McKinley places Alaska under military rule.[19]

events.description: The African National Congress is founded, under the name South African Native National Congress (SANNC).
events.html: • 1912 – The African National Congress is founded, under the name South African Native National Congress (SANNC).[20]

events.description: U.S. President Woodrow Wilson announces his "Fourteen Points" as conditions for ending World War I.
events.html: • 1918 – U.S. President Woodrow Wilson announces his "Fourteen Points" as conditions for ending World War I.[21]

events.description: The steel strike of 1919 ends in failure for the Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel and Tin Workers labor union.
events.html: • 1920 – The steel strike of 1919 ends in failure for the Amalgamated Association of Iron, Steel and Tin Workers labor union.[22]

entities.name: Amalgamated Association of Iron and Steel Workers

events.description: Crown Prince Nguyễn Phúc Vĩnh Thuỵ is crowned emperor of Vietnam, the country's last monarch.
events.html: • 1926 – Crown Prince Nguyễn Phúc Vĩnh Thuỵ is crowned emperor of Vietnam, the country's last monarch.[23]

events.description: Abdul-Aziz ibn Saud is crowned King of Hejaz.
events.html: • 1926 – Abdul-Aziz ibn Saud is crowned King of Hejaz.[24]

events.description: Kashf-e hijab decree is made and immediately enforced by Reza Shah, Iran's head of state, banning the wearing of Islamic veils in public.
events.html: • 1936 – Kashf-e hijab decree is made and immediately enforced by Reza Shah, Iran's head of state, banning the wearing of Islamic veils in public.[25]

events.description: World War II: Britain introduces food rationing.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: Britain introduces food rationing.[26]

events.description: World War II: Philippine Commonwealth troops under the Philippine Commonwealth Army units enter the province of Ilocos Sur in Northern Luzon and attack invading Japanese Imperial forces.
events.html: • 1945 – World War II: Philippine Commonwealth troops under the Philippine Commonwealth Army units enter the province of Ilocos Sur in Northern Luzon and attack invading Japanese Imperial forces.[27]

events.description: Andrei Zhdanov, Chairman of the Finnish Allied Commission, submitted to the Finnish War Criminal Court an interrogation report by General Erich Buschenhagen, a German prisoner of war, on the contacts between Finnish and German military personnel before the Continuation War and a copy of Hitler's Barbarossa plan.
events.html: • 1946 – Andrei Zhdanov, Chairman of the Finnish Allied Commission, submitted to the Finnish War Criminal Court an interrogation report by General Erich Buschenhagen, a German prisoner of war, on the contacts between Finnish and German military personnel before the Continuation War and a copy of Hitler's Barbarossa plan.[28]

events.description: Operation Auca: Five U.S. missionaries are killed by the Waorani of Ecuador shortly after making first contact.
events.html: • 1956 – Operation Auca: Five U.S. missionaries are killed by the Waorani of Ecuador shortly after making first contact.[29]

events.description: Charles de Gaulle is proclaimed as the first President of the French Fifth Republic.
events.html: • 1959 – Charles de Gaulle is proclaimed as the first President of the French Fifth Republic.[30]

events.description: In France a referendum supports Charles de Gaulle's policies in Algeria.
events.html: • 1961 – In France a referendum supports Charles de Gaulle's policies in Algeria.[31]

events.description: President Lyndon B. Johnson declares a "War on Poverty" in the United States.
events.html: • 1964 – President Lyndon B. Johnson declares a "War on Poverty" in the United States.[32]

events.description: Bowing to international pressure, President of Pakistan Zulfikar Ali Bhutto releases Bengali leader Sheikh Mujibur Rahman from prison, who had been arrested after declaring the independence of Bangladesh.
events.html: • 1972 – Bowing to international pressure, President of Pakistan Zulfikar Ali Bhutto releases Bengali leader Sheikh Mujibur Rahman from prison, who had been arrested after declaring the independence of Bangladesh.[33]

events.description: Soviet space mission Luna 21 is launched.
events.html: • 1973 – Soviet space mission Luna 21 is launched.[34]

events.description: Watergate scandal: The trial of seven men accused of illegal entry into Democratic Party headquarters at Watergate begins.
events.html: • 1973 – Watergate scandal: The trial of seven men accused of illegal entry into Democratic Party headquarters at Watergate begins.[35]

events.description: Ella T. Grasso becomes Governor of Connecticut, the first woman to serve as a Governor in the United States other than by succeeding her husband.
events.html: • 1975 – Ella T. Grasso becomes Governor of Connecticut, the first woman to serve as a Governor in the United States other than by succeeding her husband.[36]

events.description: Three bombs explode in Moscow, Russia, Soviet Union, within 37 minutes, killing seven. The bombings are attributed to an Armenian separatist group.
events.html: • 1977 – Three bombs explode in Moscow, Russia, Soviet Union, within 37 minutes, killing seven. The bombings are attributed to an Armenian separatist group.[37]

events.description: A local farmer reports a UFO sighting in Trans-en-Provence, France, claimed to be "perhaps the most completely and carefully documented sighting of all time".
events.html: • 1981 – A local farmer reports a UFO sighting in Trans-en-Provence, France, claimed to be "perhaps the most completely and carefully documented sighting of all time".[38]

events.description: Breakup of the Bell System: In the United States, AT&T agrees to divest itself of twenty-two subdivisions.
events.html: • 1982 – Breakup of the Bell System: In the United States, AT&T agrees to divest itself of twenty-two subdivisions.[36]

events.description: Kegworth air disaster: British Midland Flight 92, a Boeing 737-400, crashes into the M1 motorway, killing 47 of the 126 people on board.
events.html: • 1989 – Kegworth air disaster: British Midland Flight 92, a Boeing 737-400, crashes into the M1 motorway, killing 47 of the 126 people on board.[39]

events.description: Russian cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov on Soyuz TM-18 leaves for Mir. He would stay on the space station until March 22, 1995, for a record 437 days in space.
events.html: • 1994 – Russian cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov on Soyuz TM-18 leaves for Mir. He would stay on the space station until March 22, 1995, for a record 437 days in space.[40]

events.description: An Antonov An-32 cargo aircraft crashes into a crowded market in Kinshasa, Zaire, killing up to 223 people on the ground; two of six crew members are also killed.
events.html: • 1996 – An Antonov An-32 cargo aircraft crashes into a crowded market in Kinshasa, Zaire, killing up to 223 people on the ground; two of six crew members are also killed.[41]

events.description: President of the United States George W. Bush signs into law the No Child Left Behind Act.
events.html: • 2002 – President of the United States George W. Bush signs into law the No Child Left Behind Act.[42]

events.description: Turkish Airlines Flight 634 crashes near Diyarbakır Airport, Turkey, killing the entire crew and 70 of the 75 passengers.
events.html: • 2003 – Turkish Airlines Flight 634 crashes near Diyarbakır Airport, Turkey, killing the entire crew and 70 of the 75 passengers.[43]

events.description: Air Midwest Flight 5481 crashes at Charlotte-Douglas Airport, in Charlotte, North Carolina, killing all 21 people on board.
events.html: • 2003 – Air Midwest Flight 5481 crashes at Charlotte-Douglas Airport, in Charlotte, North Carolina, killing all 21 people on board.[44]

events.description: The RMS Queen Mary 2, then the largest ocean liner ever built, is christened by her namesake's granddaughter, Queen Elizabeth II.
events.html: • 2004 – The RMS Queen Mary 2, then the largest ocean liner ever built, is christened by her namesake's granddaughter, Queen Elizabeth II.[45]

events.description: The nuclear sub USS San Francisco collides at full speed with an undersea mountain south of Guam. One man is killed, but the sub surfaces and is repaired.
events.html: • 2005 – The nuclear sub USS San Francisco collides at full speed with an undersea mountain south of Guam. One man is killed, but the sub surfaces and is repaired.[46]

events.description: A 6.1-magnitude earthquake in northern Costa Rica kills 15 people and injures 32.
events.html: • 2009 – A 6.1-magnitude earthquake in northern Costa Rica kills 15 people and injures 32.[47]

events.description: Gunmen from an offshoot of the Front for the Liberation of the Enclave of Cabinda attack a bus carrying the Togo national football team on its way to the 2010 Africa Cup of Nations, killing three people and injuring another nine.
events.html: • 2010 – Gunmen from an offshoot of the Front for the Liberation of the Enclave of Cabinda attack a bus carrying the Togo national football team on its way to the 2010 Africa Cup of Nations, killing three people and injuring another nine.[48]

entities.name: Front for the Liberation of the Enclave of Cabinda

events.description: Sitting US Congresswoman Gabby Giffords is shot in the head along with 18 others in a mass shooting in Tucson, Arizona. Giffords survived the assassination attempt, but six others died, including John Roll, a federal judge.
events.html: • 2011 – Sitting US Congresswoman Gabby Giffords is shot in the head along with 18 others in a mass shooting in Tucson, Arizona. Giffords survived the assassination attempt, but six others died, including John Roll, a federal judge.[49]

events.description: Joaquín Guzmán, widely regarded as the world's most powerful drug trafficker, is recaptured following his escape from a maximum security prison in Mexico.
events.html: • 2016 – Joaquín Guzmán, widely regarded as the world's most powerful drug trafficker, is recaptured following his escape from a maximum security prison in Mexico.[50]

events.description: West Air Sweden Flight 294 crashes near the Swedish reservoir of Akkajaure; both pilots, the only people on board, are killed.
events.html: • 2016 – West Air Sweden Flight 294 crashes near the Swedish reservoir of Akkajaure; both pilots, the only people on board, are killed.[51]

events.description: Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752 crashes immediately after takeoff at Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport; all 176 on board are killed. The plane was shot down by an Iranian anti-aircraft missile.
events.html: • 2020 – Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752 crashes immediately after takeoff at Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport; all 176 on board are killed. The plane was shot down by an Iranian anti-aircraft missile.[52]
